06959nmm a2200817Ia 9781479873760DE-B159720240328111612.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240328t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814798737607 a10.18574/nyu/9781479873760.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)681165  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLAW0320002bisacsh04aThe New Deportations Delirium :bInterdisciplinary Responses /ced. by M. Brinton Lykes, Daniel Kanstroom. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCitizenship and Migration in the Americas ;v700tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tForeword: Mayan Migrants Speak Out -- tIntroduction: Migration, Detention, and Deportation: Dilemmas and Responses -- tPart I: The Legal, Administrative, and Political Responses -- t1. Unhappy Families: The Failings of Immigration Law for Families That Are Not All Alike -- t2. Improving Conditions of Confinement for Immigrant Detainees: Guideposts Toward a Civil System of Civil Detention -- t3. You Be the Judge: Who Should Preside Over Immigration Cases, Where, and How? -- t4. Immigration Reform: Will New Political Calculations and New Actors Overcome Enforcement Inertia? -- tPart II. Interdisciplinary Research, Advocacy, and Actions for and with Migrants Affected by Detention and Deportation -- t5. Legal and Social Work Responses to the Detained and Deported: Interdisciplinary Reflections and Actions -- t6. Immigrants Facing Detention and Deportation: Psychosocial and Mental Health Issues, Assessment, and Intervention for Individuals and Families -- t7. Participatory Action Research with Transnational and Mixed- Status Families: Understanding and Responding to Post– 9/11 Threats in Guatemala and the United States -- t8. Unwelcome Returns: The Alienation of the New American Diaspora in Salvadoran Society -- tAbout the Editors -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince 1996, when the deportation laws were hardened, millions of migrants to the U.S., including many long-term legal permanent residents with “green cards,” have experienced summary arrest, incarceration without bail, transfer to remote detention facilities, and deportation without counsel-a life-time banishment from what is, in many cases, the only country they have ever known. U.S.-based families and communities face the loss of a worker, neighbor, spouse, parent, or child. Many of the deported are “sentenced home” to a country which they only knew as an infant, whose language they do not speak, or where a family lives in extreme poverty or indebtedness for not yet being able to pay the costs of their previous migration. But what does this actually look like and what are the systems and processes and who are the people who are enforcing deportation policies and practices? The New Deportations Delirium responds to these questions.Taken as a whole, the volume raises consciousness about the complexities of the issues and argues for the interdisciplinary dialogue and response. Over the course of the book, deportation policy is debated by lawyers, judges, social workers, researchers, and clinical and community psychologists as well as educators, researchers, and community activists. The New Deportations Delirium presents a fresh conversation and urges a holistic response to the complex realities facing not only migrants but also the wider U.S. society in which they have sought a better life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 7aLAW / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh1 aArgueta, Luis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBelanger, Maurice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.lo